Ordinance No. 24-2014 - Amending Section 59-32 Accessory buildings
Approve Ordinance No. 24-2014 Amending the Land Development Code to resolve issues
related to the setbacks for accessory structures in the R-3 zoning district.
On February 11, 2014, the City Council approved an advisability to resolve an issue related to
setback criteria for rear yard accessory structures in the High Density Residential (R-3) zoning
district. Section 59-32 of the Land Development Code establishes setbacks for accessory
structures within the residential zoning districts. In general, the rear yard setbacks established for
accessory buildings, attached screen porches, swimming pools and pool enclosures are
significantly larger than in other residential zoning districts.
By way of comparison, the setbacks for primary structures are identical for the R-2 and R-3
zoning districts. This issue was brought to staffs attention, as there is a property owner who
cannot add accessory structures to their home in the R-3 due to the current setbacks.
The proposed changes include a reduction of the rear yard setbacks for accessory structures in
the R-3 zoning district from 25 feet to 10 feet (On May 27, 2014, the City Council requested the
R-3 accessory structure rear setback be reduced to 5 feet), the side yard setback table was
updated consistent with the rear yard table, Buildings and Structures are listed as detached as
defined in the Code, and the distinction of an accessory structure less than 120 square feet as
1. Recommend Approval of the Ordinance as written.
2. Recommend Approval of the Ordinance with changes.
3. Do not Recommend Approval of the Ordinance.

outdoor storage, allow outdoor storage in the M-1 zoning district,
and amend permitted and conditional uses in the M-1.
Approve First Reading of Ordinance No. 23-2014 Amending the Land Development Code
by adding outdoor storage definition in Section 27-11 "Definitions", adding Section 59-484(h) to
allow outdoor storage as a conditional use accessory to a primary use with a principal building in
the M-1 zoning district, adding warehousing and industrial service type uses in Section 59-482

The purpose of this ordinance is to amend the Citys Land Development Code to address issues

was to allow a landscaped buffer as a screening option.

Ordinance to add Outdoor Storage and Amend Conditional

page.text: Staff is requesting the Planning and Zoning Commission
consider an ordinance to amend the Land Development
Code to allow outdoor storage in the M-1 zoning district and
The purpose of this ordinance is to amend the Citys Land Development Code (LDC) to address
issues related to outdoor storage and conditional uses in the Light Industrial Services and
Warehousing (M-1) zoning district. The staff received two separate directives from City Council to
allow a limited amount of outdoor storage in industrially zoned areas and bring the M-1 zoning
district into conformity with its stated purpose and intent. The ordinance attempts to resolve both
On February 25, 2014, the City Council approved an advisability to draft amendments to the LDR
to address outdoor storage. The staff reviewed the Citys code, the codes of other jurisdictions and
conducted a windshield survey of the City. Based on this review and the conditions observed it was
determined to limit the amendment to the M-1 zoning district with the possibility of additional
The LDR currently allows a limited amount of accessory outdoor storage in certain commercial and
industrially zoning districts. The Industrial (M-2) is the only zoning district that permits outdoor
storage as a primary use. In each district screening and buffering criteria are specified depending
on the type of use and adjacency to other uses. The M-2 and Planned Industrial Development
(PID) zoning districts refer to the criteria specified in Section 35-38 of the LDR, which requires a
minimum 6 foot high wood fence, masonry wall or opaque landscaping when outdoor storage
areas are located adjacent to residential uses. The PID zoning district further restricts the location
of outdoor storage areas behind a building, within a totally enclosed wall, wood fence or
landscaped chain link fence regardless the adjacent uses. The M-2 zoning district does not
prescribe additional screening criteria. The Regional Commercial (RC) zoning district simply states
that lumber and building supplies not be visible from surrounding uses. Outdoor storage related to
auto sales in the RC and Commercial Marine (CM) zoning districts do not appear to require
P and Z Regular - June 4, 2014 - 6:00 PM
screening; rather, such uses are required to provide a 2 foot perimeter wall, hedge or berm
[Sec. 35-38]. It is important to note that the storage of vehicles is separate from the outside
display of merchandise related to automobiles in the RC, CM, Community Commercial (CC), and
Neighborhood Commercial (NC) zoning districts. The following table summarizes the outdoor
storage types permitted in some of the zoning districts.
Permitted accessory to marine, retail and
accessory to retail sales if in the downtown
Permitted accessory to auto sales or retail
The staff reviewed the codes of other jurisdictions with similar industrial classifications, including
the Cities of Melbourne and Tampa and Brevard County. Melbourne does not define outdoor
storage other than to specify where it is permitted. The City allows accessory building and
contractor storage in its M-1 and M-2 industrial zoning districts but only if walled in [Zoning
Article V Melbourne]. Tampa defines open storage as the keeping, outside of a completely
enclosed building, of any materials, goods, merchandise, equipment or vehicles. The City
specifically permits open storage as a primary use in the industrial districts and as a conditional use
in its commercial intense district. Tampa requires screening from the street 100 feet from the
right-of-way unless a permanent structure shields the storage area. The screen must be a 6-8 foot
masonry wall or decorative fence even if within 200 feet from residential [Sec. 27-282.12 Tampa].
Brevard defines outdoor storage in terms of what it should not be: the excessive accumulation of
material, items or junk unless on properties zoned for junk yards, automobile wrecking yards, or
metal salvage yards. Outside storage is allowed in industrial zoning districts and outside storage is
specifically listed as not permitted in all other districts. Such uses must be 75 feet from rights-of-
way, enclosed from right-of-way and adjacent properties not zoned industrial with a 6-8 opaque
wall, fence or landscape berm and stacked materials may not exceed the enclosure height [Sec.
62-1542(8)b Brevard]. Further, the outside bulk storage of plant nursery related items may be
approved through a conditional use permit in certain intense commercial zoning districts.
On March 6, 2014, the planning and code enforcement staff conducted a windshield survey of
several industrial and commercial properties throughout the City. The staff observed the existence
of what would generally be considered outdoor storage of retail related goods, construction and
building materials, containers, vehicles and in some cases junk. On each property, the outdoor
storage appeared to be accessory to a permitted, primary use. The outdoor storage on a few
properties was screened with a chain link fence and was visible from the right-of-way.
: The staff found a few instances where the M-1 light industrial zoning district had
been approved in areas with the High Intensity Commercial Future Land Use (FLU) category. The
City recently approved an amendment to the comprehensive plan that limits the M-1 zoning district
to only be consistent with the Industrial FLU category [Ord. No. 7-2014]. This will prevent further
encroachment of the M-1 zoning district into inappropriate areas. The M-1 requires a 75 foot
setback from all property lines for manufacturing and assembly type uses that are in enclosed
structures. Bulk or outdoor storage is specifically prohibited for wholesale and warehouse type
uses. There are instances where it appears outdoor storage could occur when related to permitted
uses such as lumber and building supplies, retail nurseries, lawn and garden supplies, mechanical,
automotive, boat or other vehicular repair. It does not appear that outdoor display is permitted in
P and Z Regular - June 4, 2014 - 6:00 PM
the M-1 district. In general, the M-1 is primarily a buffer district between heavy industrial and
commercial activities and has the potential of being located near or adjacent to residential uses
Based on these findings the staff is recommending draft definitions and minor revisions to the LDR
primarily to the M-1 district. The recommended definitions include the terms outdoor storage,
zoning lot, parcel, and use. The staff is also suggesting that if outdoor storage is allowed in the M-
1 zoning district that it be a limited accessory use as proposed in the draft text amendment.
On July 13, 2013, the City Council approved an advisability to draft amendments to the LDR to
address conditional uses in the M-1 zoning district. Section 59-481 sets forth the purpose of the M-
1 zoning district as providing areas for service and repair establishments, personal storage
facilities and warehousing, light manufacturing, processing and distribution. However,
warehousing and light manufacturing, processing and distribution are conditional uses rather than
permitted uses. This has limited the functionality of the M-1 zoning classification for new and
expanding businesses in the City. In addition, it can be argued that the confusion resulting from
the need for a conditional use permit has hindered economic development efforts. The staff sought
and received an advisability to make light manufacturing and warehousing permitted uses, as
implied by the name of the M-1 zoning district. Specifically, the staff proposed allowing the existing
Manufacturing, assembly and fabrication of products within a completely enclosed structure
permitted uses in the M-1 zoning district.
On February 11, 2014, the City Council adopted Comprehensive Plan Amendment 2013-01E
amending Policies 1.8.8 and 1.9.9 of the Future Land Use Element establishing Economic
Opportunity Districts and updating the Industrial and High Intensity Commercial land use
categories (Ord. No. 7-2014). Policy 1.9.9.G specifically addressed the need to remedy the
incursion of M-1 zoning into areas with the High Intensity Commercial land use. All areas with M-1
zoning and with the High Intensity Commercial land use prior to September 2013 are deemed
consistent with the High Intensity Commercial designation. The staff is therefore proposing to
Wholesale, warehouse, storage, manufacturing, assembly and fabrication
specified in the M-1 zoning district as conditional uses in the High Intensity Commercial and as
permitted uses in the Industrial land use designations.
The staff requests the Planning and Zoning Commission consider approving the ordinance.

Approve an ordinance to amend the zoning map.
The applicant, Rodney M. Honeycutt, on behalf of the owner, 2305 Garden Street LLC and 9 Williams
Avenue LLC, is requesting to rezone two parcels located 2305 Garden Street and 9 Williams Avenue
from the Office Professional (OP) district to Community Commercial (CC) in the Commercial Low
Intensity Future Land Use (FLU) for purposes of constructing a 3,500+ sq.ft. building with a restaurant
and office/retail uses. The parcels are located at the southeast corner of Garden Street and Williams
Avenue and encompass approximately 34,412+ sq.ft (0.79 acres).
P and Z Regular - June 4, 2014 - 6:00 PM

text.b: Planning and Zoning Commission Agenda Item: REZ No. 2-2014

page.text: The parcels are located adjacent to Garden Street, which is an approximately 2,000+ linear foot
commercial corridor and connector between the Downtown area and regional commercial centers near
Interstate 95. This segment of Garden Street between Williams Road to Hilltop Drive has a
Comprehensive Plan Future Land Use Map (FLU) designation of Commercial Low Intensity. The
purpose of the land use is to accommodate retail and office uses at the neighborhood scale that serve the
immediate area. The location of the land use is intended to buffer the surrounding single-family uses from
the more intense commercial uses that bookend the area; primarily, the Commercial High Intensity FLU
to the west near I-95 and the Downtown Mixed Use FLU immediately to the east. The properties to the
north and south of the area are Single Family Medium Density (R-1B). The area to the east is CC and
Light Industrial Services and Warehousing (M-1). The proposed CC rezoning is consistent with the
The request if approved will be the second adopted CC rezoning on this segment of Garden Street. In
2000 the property located at 2505 Garden Street was rezoned from OP to CC to permit a retail use. A pool
supply store currently occupies the site.
The CC zoning request is consistent with the Commercial Low Intensity FLU. The land use allows a
Floor Area Ratio (FAR) of 1.0 or 34,412 sq.ft. of non-residential uses. Current environmental and
development standards limit the build out potential of the site, including a maximum height of 35 feet
[Sec. 59-266] and a 25% maximum impervious pavement coverage requirement [Sec. 35-61].
The entire segment was zoned Office Professional (OP) in 1993. The OP zoning district permits a variety
of low impact uses including professional, business, medical, financial and personal services. Retail is not
a permitted use in the OP district with the exception of limited supporting and conditional use activities
such as business and art supplies, gift shops, florists, restaurants and coffee shop without drive-thrus.
Approval of the rezoning request to Community Commercial (CC) will allow these supporting retail
activities as permitted uses. In addition, the rezoning to CC will permit the retail sale and service of
vehicles and appliances, food markets, car wash, fuel stations, schools and colleges, and restaurants.
Certain conditional uses allowed in the CC such as commercial recreation and amusement parks may be
more intense than the area can accommodate.
As an alternative, rezoning the properties to the Neighborhood Commercial (NC) zoning district could
accommodate the requested restaurant/office/retail uses and prohibit the relatively intense uses permitted
in the CC zoning. The NC appears to be a hybrid of the low intensity OP zoning and higher intensity CC
zoning. The NC specifically prohibits intense retail uses such as automotive sales and service, markets
and outdoor display or service of household and garden appliances. The NC zoning district is consistent
with the Commercial Low Intensity FLU for the same reasons described below and is an appropriate
alternative classification if the CC is found undesirable.
Section 47-102(c) of the Land Development Code (LDC) lists the review criteria under which the
Planning and Zoning Commission and the City Council review rezoning applications. The following are
staffs findings regarding the rezoning request to CC.
1. Comprehensive Plan Consistency Statement. The rezoning request in REZ application No. 2-2014 is
consistent with the following Objectives and Policies of the Comprehensive Plan.
[Future Land Use Element (FLUE)] Objective: 1.9 and subsequent Policies 1.9.1 through 1.9.8:
Commercial Land Uses. The City of Titusville shall provide for appropriate and adequate land for
commercial land uses through the designation of Commercial High Intensity and Commercial Low
Intensity land use designations on the Future Land Use Map.

Sites for low intensity commercial development shall be located near intersections. Intersection
locations are preferred to linear developments. The City shall not introduce, approve or allow
commercial land uses in an area where single family land uses are the predominant land use of the
area unless the proposed new land use is consistent with a redevelopment plan or formal study
Land development regulations shall include additional requirements for low intensity commercial
and residential land use compatibility. Such requirements shall address, but not be limited to,
floor area ratio, maximum lot coverage, maximum impervious surface ratio, screening, height,
setbacks, glare, landscaping, and architectural compatibility.
Low Intensity Commercial uses oriented towards neighborhood needs and convenience factors
and should be designated for limited retail and sales use and/or commercial/professional mixed
The City shall further delineate, through its land development regulations,
commercial zoning mechanisms to create zoning categories of neighborhood commercial, community
commercial, regional commercial, and office. Each category shall be further delineated with appropriate
1.1. Public facilities are available and concurrent with the development per the Comprehensive Plan
and Land Development Regulations. The properties are located in the Citys urban service area.
Water and sewer is available to serve the property and is available concurrent with development.
Transportation impacts were determined based on the most intense allowable use in the CC and
the proposed development. A 3,500 sq.ft. restaurant with drive-thru will generate approximately
2,480 daily vehicular trips [ITE 2007]. This will not impact the level of service (LOS) on SR 406
Solid Waste is available to serve the property.
1.2. Public streets are adequate to access the property. The properties have approximately 175 feet of
frontage on Garden Street and 178 feet on Williams Road. Garden Street is an arterial and
Williams is a local road. Right of way permits are required with any new development.
1.3. The land will support the proposed development and should not be subject to flooding or other
physical constraints provided new development adheres to the requirement specified in Chapter
35 Article III Stormwater Management, Conservation and Aquifer Protection of the Code.
1.4. Environmental impact. The only discernable environmental impact of the proposed rezoning is its
location in an Area of Critical Concern. New development must adhere to the performance
standards Chapter 35 Article III Stormwater Management, Conservation and Aquifer Protection
2. The rezoning application is consistent with the Land Development Regulations. The applicant
requests the ability to construct a 3,500 sq.ft. building with a 2,000 sq.ft. office or retail area and
1,500 sq.ft. restaurant. The proposed uses are consistent with the requested zoning district. New
development shall adhere to the special design criteria specified in Section 59-266 of the Code
regarding commercial zoning districts in the Low Intensity Commercial FLU.

text.b: Planning and Zoning Commission Agenda Item: REZ No. 2-2014

page.text: 3. Consistency of existing zoning. The existing zoning, if deemed consistent with the Comprehensive
Plan, shall be presumed correct unless substantial change in the area has occurred since the original
zoning. The current OP and proposed CC zoning districts are consistent with the Commercial Low
4. The intensity of the current and proposed zoning are the same and consistent with the development in
the area. This rezoning is not likely to depreciate the property values in the area.
5. The application is consistent with zoning in the area. The roadway segment between Williams Road
to Hilltop Drive is OP zoning with the exception of a rezoning of a nearby lot to CC in 2000. The
properties to the north and south of the area are Single Family Medium Density (R-1B). The area to
the east is CC and Light Industrial Services and Warehousing (M-1). The proposed CC rezoning is
consistent with the zoning in the area.
6. Neighoborhood impact. That the application will protect the public health, safety, morals or welfare
of the general public. With the possible exception of certain conditional uses described above, the
staff does not believe the development of this property with the uses allowed in the CC zoning district
will create a nuisance to the general public.
7. Buffering and screening from adjacent uses. The property is adjacent to existing single family homes.
Development of the property shall adhere to the buffer and screening criteria of Chapter 35 Article II
Environmental Protection and Conservation of the Code.
8. Substantial reasons why the property cannot be used in the existing zoning district. Retail and
restaurants are not permitted uses in the existing OP zoning. The applicant requests the ability to
construct a single building with restaurant and office or retail.
Based on the above findings, the staff recommends approval of application REZ No. 2-2014 to rezone
parcels located at 2305 Garden Street and 9 Williams Avenue from the Office Professional (OP) district
to Community Commercial (CC) in the Commercial Low Intensity Future Land Use.

The applicant is making this request to allow for the expansion of a church. The recently
adopted Indian River City Neighborhood (IRCN) zoning district specifically requires a place of
religious assembly to be located on property that has frontage on either a collector or arterial
roadway [Sec. 59-812(b)]. Since Knox McRae is the only qualified road this requirement would
P and Z Regular - June 4, 2014 - 6:00 PM

appears the intent of the zoning requirement is to prevent the development of a large assembly
use in a residential neighborhood with multiple points of egress on local roads. If the request is
approved the Planning and Zoning Commission should consider prohibiting direct vehicular
access from Maple Place if a religious assembly use is constructed on the lot.
The staff finds the request will not impact City services and recommends approval of Right-of-
Way Vacate application ROW No. 3-2014 and the adoption of the related resolution.
